00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:34.192
The affect of temperature.
If you are in the gas phase,

00:01:34.192 --> 00:01:38.929
it is sort of the qualitative
observation that if you increase

00:01:38.929 --> 00:01:41.569
the temperature the rate
increases.

00:01:41.569 --> 00:01:46.383
You've probably sort of thought
about this, that if you want to

00:01:46.383 --> 00:01:49.722
make something go faster,
you add some heat.

00:01:49.722 --> 00:01:54.070
Today we are going to talk
about quantitative affects and

00:01:54.070 --> 00:01:58.884
how you can actually calculate a
change in rate constant if the

00:01:58.884 --> 00:02:03.000
temperature of the reaction is
changed.

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:09.293
Here we go back to 1889.
That is when Arrhenius plotted

00:02:09.293 --> 00:02:13.139
rate constants versus
temperature.

00:02:13.139 --> 00:02:17.917
And he was looking to get a
straight line.

00:02:17.917 --> 00:02:23.860
He found that if he used the
natural log of the rate

00:02:23.860 --> 00:02:30.154
constants and plotted that
against inverse temperature,

00:02:30.154 --> 00:02:36.715
he got a straight line.
Here is what one of those plots

00:02:36.715 --> 00:02:40.218
look like.
The rate constants are varying

00:02:40.218 --> 00:02:43.547
exponentially with inverse
temperature.

00:02:43.547 --> 00:02:47.226
On one axis,
we have the natural log of the

00:02:47.226 --> 00:02:50.204
rate constant k.
On the other axis,

00:02:50.204 --> 00:02:55.109
we have one over temperature.
And so this is the equation

00:02:55.109 --> 00:03:00.603
that is being plotted.
Again, we have natural log of k

00:03:00.603 --> 00:03:03.458
on one axis.
That is rate constant.

00:03:03.458 --> 00:03:06.648
The other axis is one over
temperature.

00:03:06.648 --> 00:03:10.931
And so if this is one over
temperature on this axis,

00:03:10.931 --> 00:03:15.717
then the slope of the line is
minus Ea, activation energy,

00:03:15.717 --> 00:03:18.488
over R, which is the gas
constant.

00:03:18.488 --> 00:03:22.603
Up here, activation energy E
sub a and R,

00:03:22.603 --> 00:03:26.549
our gas constant.
And the intercept of the line,

00:03:26.549 --> 00:03:31.000
then, is the natural log of
capital A.

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:34.250
And capital A has several
different names.

00:03:34.250 --> 00:03:38.452
You will see it listed in
different books as different

00:03:38.452 --> 00:03:41.465
things.
I think our book usually refers

00:03:41.465 --> 00:03:45.271
to it as factor A,
or the pre-exponential factor.

00:03:45.271 --> 00:03:48.204
And it would have the same
units as k.

00:03:48.204 --> 00:03:52.168
If one plots natural log of
rate constants over one

00:03:52.168 --> 00:03:56.846
temperature, one could determine
the activation energy for a

00:03:56.846 --> 00:04:02.000
reaction or the factor A for a
particular reaction.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:07.033
These quantities,
factor A and activation energy,

00:04:07.033 --> 00:04:11.543
are dependent on the reaction
being studied.

00:04:11.543 --> 00:04:16.576
There will be a particular
measured value for one

00:04:16.576 --> 00:04:21.715
particular reaction.
Let's think a little bit more

00:04:21.715 --> 00:04:27.902
about what these quantities are.
Factor A, is it temperature

00:04:27.902 --> 00:04:30.000
dependent?

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:39.943
No, it is not temperature
dependent.

00:04:39.943 --> 00:04:44.563
So what is it?
Well, if we look over here,

00:04:44.563 --> 00:04:51.436
the natural log of A is going
to equal the natural log of k at

00:04:51.436 --> 00:04:56.619
zero, over here,
and that means when one over T

00:04:56.619 --> 00:05:02.566
is approximately zero.
At what kinds of temperatures

00:05:02.566 --> 00:05:06.637
would one over T be
approximately zero?

00:05:06.637 --> 00:05:10.884
Really, really big.
Factor A is the rate constant

00:05:10.884 --> 00:05:15.575
for that reaction at some
infinitely huge temperature.

00:05:15.575 --> 00:05:20.619
That is the maximum value that
you could get for that rate

00:05:20.619 --> 00:05:23.362
constant.
At really, really huge

00:05:23.362 --> 00:05:27.964
temperature that is what it is.
It is not temperature

00:05:27.964 --> 00:05:32.031
dependent.
It is a quantity that is the

00:05:32.031 --> 00:05:36.675
sort of maximum rate constant at
the biggest temperature that you

00:05:36.675 --> 00:05:39.433
can think of.
That is what factor A is.

00:05:39.433 --> 00:05:43.786
What about activation energy?
Is that going to be temperature

00:05:43.786 --> 00:05:46.471
dependent?
No, it won't be temperature

00:05:46.471 --> 00:05:49.229
dependent either.
You can calculate it.

00:05:49.229 --> 00:05:53.002
It is the slope of the line.
So you can get it out of

00:05:53.002 --> 00:05:56.630
plotting these values,
but it is going to depend on

00:05:56.630 --> 00:06:02.000
the reaction being studied,
not the particular temperature.

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:05.536
And this is going to be
important in a few minutes

00:06:05.536 --> 00:06:09.432
because we are going to be
talking about the effects of

00:06:09.432 --> 00:06:13.329
rate constants on different
temperatures and looking at

00:06:13.329 --> 00:06:16.000
equations and doing some
calculations.

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:18.597
Okay.
We can rewrite this equation in

00:06:18.597 --> 00:06:22.711
a couple of different ways.
You will see that equation for

00:06:22.711 --> 00:06:25.958
the straight line that Arrhenius
came up with.

00:06:25.958 --> 00:06:30.000
It is often called the
Arrhenius equation.

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:34.817
And it can be written basically
just reversing these two terms,

00:06:34.817 --> 00:06:37.926
I guess because it looks better
that way.

00:06:37.926 --> 00:06:42.433
I am not really sure why you
cannot just keep it like that,

00:06:42.433 --> 00:06:46.552
but you will see it this way.
And you will also see it

00:06:46.552 --> 00:06:50.204
rewritten this way.
Instead of natural log of k,

00:06:50.204 --> 00:06:52.691
you would see it as solved for
k.

00:06:52.691 --> 00:06:57.198
Here, the rate constant is
equal to A, which is this factor

00:06:57.198 --> 00:06:59.685
A.
This rate constant at infinity

00:06:59.685 --> 00:07:04.658
huge temperatures times e to the
minus Ea, the activation energy,

00:07:04.658 --> 00:07:10.000
over RT.
So you will also see this

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:13.839
equation this way.
It is a way of figuring out if

00:07:13.839 --> 00:07:18.000
you know the activation energy
and you know factor A,

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:21.759
you can calculate rate
constants at a particular

00:07:21.759 --> 00:07:24.720
temperature.
It is not only gases that

00:07:24.720 --> 00:07:28.399
behave in this way,
that exhibit this Arrhenius

00:07:28.399 --> 00:07:32.948
behavior.
And you can apply these

00:07:32.948 --> 00:07:39.743
equations to other systems.
And let's just look at one

00:07:39.743 --> 00:07:47.820
other example of something that
behaves with Arrhenius behavior.

00:07:47.820 --> 00:07:50.641
What is that?
Crickets.

00:07:50.641 --> 00:07:56.666
How many of you have heard
crickets in the wild?

00:07:56.666 --> 00:08:01.901
Almost everybody.
I spent some years as a summer

00:08:01.901 --> 00:08:04.691
camp counselor,
and we always had kids coming

00:08:04.691 --> 00:08:08.494
to the country from the city.
And there would be crickets and

00:08:08.494 --> 00:08:11.030
bull frogs.
And these poor kids that grew

00:08:11.030 --> 00:08:14.770
up right outside a hospital
where all night long there would

00:08:14.770 --> 00:08:18.384
be ambulances going by and
traffic and helicopters and all

00:08:18.384 --> 00:08:22.188
sorts of things would sleep fine
at home, but then they would

00:08:22.188 --> 00:08:26.118
come to the country and couldn't
sleep a wink because of all of

00:08:26.118 --> 00:08:28.717
this noise.
The country is not as quiet as

00:08:28.717 --> 00:08:33.149
people think it is.
Crickets will respond to

00:08:33.149 --> 00:08:38.164
temperature, and so they
actually chirp faster when it is

00:08:38.164 --> 00:08:40.850
hotter.
If you are out camping,

00:08:40.850 --> 00:08:46.223
you can count how many chirps
there are in 14 seconds and add

00:08:46.223 --> 00:08:50.522
that to 40 and get the
temperature in Fahrenheit.

00:08:50.522 --> 00:08:54.373
Has anyone actually tried this?
Did it work?

00:08:54.373 --> 00:08:57.955
You think so.
Did you have a control of a

00:08:57.955 --> 00:09:01.201
thermometer with you?
No.

00:09:01.201 --> 00:09:05.422
It probably works better if you
don't actually have the control,

00:09:05.422 --> 00:09:09.175
but it should theoretically
work if you can do a good job

00:09:09.175 --> 00:09:11.855
counting.
That is an example of a non-gas

00:09:11.855 --> 00:09:14.000
exhibiting this behavior.

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:23.097
All right.
Let's talk more about the

00:09:23.097 --> 00:09:26.991
activation energy.
We are going to talk a lot

00:09:26.991 --> 00:09:32.126
about activation energy today.
Activation energy Ea.

00:09:32.126 --> 00:09:37.696
If you have two molecules
coming together and colliding,

00:09:37.696 --> 00:09:42.962
sometimes they will form
products, and sometimes they

00:09:42.962 --> 00:09:46.911
will just fall away back into
reactants.

00:09:46.911 --> 00:09:51.164
Not every collision will result
in product.

00:09:51.164 --> 00:09:55.316
Why is that?
Only the collisions that have

00:09:55.316 --> 00:10:02.000
the right amount of energy can
go on and form products.

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:06.719
Really, what activation energy
is, is some critical amount of

00:10:06.719 --> 00:10:11.202
energy that is required to go on
and result in a reaction.

00:10:11.202 --> 00:10:14.662
Only the molecules with that
critical energy,

00:10:14.662 --> 00:10:18.595
when they come together,
they will go onto product.

00:10:18.595 --> 00:10:22.764
Other molecules will come
together, and they will just

00:10:22.764 --> 00:10:27.011
fall apart, because they won't
be able to overcome this

00:10:27.011 --> 00:10:35.159
activation energy barrier.
Let's look at the affect of

00:10:35.159 --> 00:10:46.050
temperature on the molecules
that have critical amounts of

00:10:46.050 --> 00:10:50.636
energy.
If we plot, then,

00:10:50.636 --> 00:11:00.000
fraction of molecules versus
kinetic energy.

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:07.323
And we can look at molecules
that have a low temperature,

00:11:07.323 --> 00:11:11.376
or molecules at low
temperature.

00:11:11.376 --> 00:11:19.484
There are some molecules at low
temperature, and we can look at

00:11:19.484 --> 00:11:25.892
some fractions of molecules at
higher temperature,

00:11:25.892 --> 00:11:34.000
and then consider the critical
energy needed to react.

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:39.368
The activation energy.
Molecules with that amount of

00:11:39.368 --> 00:11:43.157
energy or more will be able to
react.

00:11:43.157 --> 00:11:47.894
And, if you look at the
fraction of molecules,

00:11:47.894 --> 00:11:53.789
then, that would have that
energy, at higher temperatures

00:11:53.789 --> 00:12:00.000
more molecules have that
critical amount of energy.

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:03.768
And at lower temperature,
fewer molecules have that

00:12:03.768 --> 00:12:07.386
critical amount of energy.
So temperature makes a

00:12:07.386 --> 00:12:09.874
difference.
At higher temperature,

00:12:09.874 --> 00:12:12.361
more things will be able to
react.

00:12:12.361 --> 00:12:16.809
That is what gets into this
observation that reactions occur

00:12:16.809 --> 00:12:20.728
faster at higher temperature.
More molecules have the

00:12:20.728 --> 00:12:24.798
critical energy needed to react
when they are at higher

00:12:24.798 --> 00:12:28.040
temperature.
At lower temperature it is more

00:12:28.040 --> 00:12:32.129
difficult.
Fewer fractions of those

00:12:32.129 --> 00:12:36.653
molecules have that critical
energy, can overcome an

00:12:36.653 --> 00:12:41.177
activation energy barrier.
Let's look at an example,

00:12:41.177 --> 00:12:46.233
now, of if you know what the
activation energy barrier is,

00:12:46.233 --> 00:12:50.580
figuring out different rate
constants at different

00:12:50.580 --> 00:12:54.217
temperatures,
how temperature is affecting

00:12:54.217 --> 00:12:59.008
the rate of the reaction.
The example that we will look

00:12:59.008 --> 00:13:05.274
at is the hydrolysis of sucrose.
And this is part of the

00:13:05.274 --> 00:13:10.019
digestive process.
And digestion is a good thing.

00:13:10.019 --> 00:13:13.776
Let's look at this particular
reaction.

00:13:13.776 --> 00:13:17.039
We are given an activation
energy.

00:13:17.039 --> 00:13:21.884
Someone has measured the
activation energy for the

00:13:21.884 --> 00:13:26.432
hydrolysis of sucrose,
108 kilojoules per mole.

00:13:26.432 --> 00:13:30.485
And someone has measured an
observed rate,

00:13:30.485 --> 00:13:38.000
a k(obs) of 1.0x10^-3 per molar
per second at body temperature.

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:43.019
Now you are asked to figure out
what, would the observed rate

00:13:43.019 --> 00:13:48.121
constant be if you lowered that
temperature, if you lowered it

00:13:48.121 --> 00:13:52.806
by 2 degrees to 35 degrees?
You could right two different

00:13:52.806 --> 00:13:56.319
expressions.
You can use Arrhenius equation

00:13:56.319 --> 00:14:00.000
and write two different
expressions.

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:03.805
Over here we have the natural
log of k one,

00:14:03.805 --> 00:14:07.985
the rate constant at one time,
and t one at that

00:14:07.985 --> 00:14:10.671
temperature.
So, the rate constant at

00:14:10.671 --> 00:14:13.805
temperature one.
That would be equal to the

00:14:13.805 --> 00:14:17.835
natural log of factor A,
again, that is not temperature

00:14:17.835 --> 00:14:20.970
dependent, minus Ea,
the activation energy,

00:14:20.970 --> 00:14:24.253
and then it is over RT.
And we write the same

00:14:24.253 --> 00:14:28.134
expression for a second
temperature and a second rate

00:14:28.134 --> 00:14:32.473
constant.
Now we can combine these two

00:14:32.473 --> 00:14:36.094
expressions and come up with one
equation.

00:14:36.094 --> 00:14:40.157
If we subtract,
we have natural log of the rate

00:14:40.157 --> 00:14:45.015
constant two minus the natural
log of rate constant one.

00:14:45.015 --> 00:14:50.492
And that can also be expressed
in terms of natural log of k two

00:14:50.492 --> 00:14:55.438
over k one.
And here we can pull out the

00:14:55.438 --> 00:15:00.297
temperature terms.
Both of these have the same

00:15:00.297 --> 00:15:04.212
expression, minus Ea over R,
the rate constant.

00:15:04.212 --> 00:15:07.276
And now we have the two
temperatures.

00:15:07.276 --> 00:15:12.468
This expression is telling us
how the rate constants are going

00:15:12.468 --> 00:15:17.659
to change with temperature for a
particular activation energy.

00:15:17.659 --> 00:15:20.468
What does this equation look
like?

00:15:20.468 --> 00:15:25.659
It should look familiar to you.
Something that we talked about

00:15:25.659 --> 00:15:30.000
before.
What was that equation called?

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:38.294
Van Hoff equation.
And instead of rate constants

00:15:38.294 --> 00:15:45.882
we had what?
Instead of rate constants there

00:15:45.882 --> 00:15:50.647
were?
Equilibrium constants.

00:15:50.647 --> 00:15:57.000
And instead of Ea we had what?

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:07.935
What tells us about how
equilibrium constants change

00:16:07.935 --> 00:16:11.561
with temperature?
If you have a reaction and you

00:16:11.561 --> 00:16:15.574
heat up the reaction,
how do you know which direction

00:16:15.574 --> 00:16:18.506
it shifts?
What is our predictive tool?

00:16:18.506 --> 00:16:22.055
Delta H, right.
This equation is similar to one

00:16:22.055 --> 00:16:25.450
we saw before.
Here we are comparing how rate

00:16:25.450 --> 00:16:29.000
constants change with
temperature.

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:32.456
And a predictive tool is the
size, the magnitude of the

00:16:32.456 --> 00:16:35.399
activation energy.
Before we were talking about

00:16:35.399 --> 00:16:38.087
how rate constants change with
temperature.

00:16:38.087 --> 00:16:40.711
And the predictive tool there
was delta H.

00:16:40.711 --> 00:16:44.104
In case you need a review of
this, we will review this

00:16:44.104 --> 00:16:48.072
actually at the end of the class
because this is very exciting.

00:16:48.072 --> 00:16:51.464
At the end of the class we come
back to Le Châtelier's

00:16:51.464 --> 00:16:54.628
principle.
And we can explain Le

00:16:54.628 --> 00:16:59.204
Châletier's principle in terms
of temperature in a different

00:16:59.204 --> 00:17:03.934
way than we did when we started
the course, because now we can

00:17:03.934 --> 00:17:08.122
think about it in terms of
activation energies and rate

00:17:08.122 --> 00:17:10.836
constants.
We will see that van Hoff

00:17:10.836 --> 00:17:13.473
equation again.
For the moment now,

00:17:13.473 --> 00:17:18.048
we are just considering how
rate constants are changing with

00:17:18.048 --> 00:17:20.995
temperature.
We can plug in our values.

00:17:20.995 --> 00:17:25.338
The initial observed rate for
the reaction at 37 degrees,

00:17:25.338 --> 00:17:31.000
and we have k two that
we are going to solve for.

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:33.284
We were given the activation
energy.

00:17:33.284 --> 00:17:36.808
And we know the gas constant,
and we were given the two

00:17:36.808 --> 00:17:39.550
temperatures.
The only tricky thing here is

00:17:39.550 --> 00:17:42.356
to remember to get your units to
cancel out.

00:17:42.356 --> 00:17:45.554
Often activation energies are
given in kilojoules,

00:17:45.554 --> 00:17:48.034
whereas your gas constant is in
joules.

00:17:48.034 --> 00:17:50.841
The temperatures here were
given in Celsius,

00:17:50.841 --> 00:17:54.627
but if you are using the gas
constant you are going to need

00:17:54.627 --> 00:17:59.000
to convert them to Kelvin for
your units to cancel.

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:03.913
The only thing tricky about
this is to make sure that your

00:18:03.913 --> 00:18:08.741
units are going to cancel.
And so we can solve this for k

00:18:08.741 --> 00:18:11.844
two.
And k two comes out to be

00:18:11.844 --> 00:18:17.189
7.6x10^-4 per molar per second.
It would be the same units as k

00:18:17.189 --> 00:18:20.810
one, and that is quite a
bit slower.

00:18:20.810 --> 00:18:24.603
We only changed our temperature
by 2 degrees,

00:18:24.603 --> 00:18:29.000
and yet the rate is quite a bit
slower.

