00:30:15.122 --> 00:30:19.098
For an elementary reaction,
increasing temperature will

00:30:19.098 --> 00:30:22.558
increase the rate.
It will get over the barrier.

00:30:22.558 --> 00:30:26.607
For an overall reaction,
for a more complicated reaction

00:30:26.607 --> 00:30:30.361
that has multiple steps,
it is not necessarily clear

00:30:30.361 --> 00:30:35.000
that temperature is going to
have this affect.

00:30:35.000 --> 00:30:37.619
And let's consider why this is
true.

00:30:37.619 --> 00:30:42.035
Let's look at the same reaction
we looked at with mechanisms

00:30:42.035 --> 00:30:46.377
last time and figure out what
all the k observed

00:30:46.377 --> 00:30:49.446
terms are.
Are there small rate constants?

00:30:49.446 --> 00:30:51.766
Are there equilibrium
constants?

00:30:51.766 --> 00:30:56.257
What does k(obs) really mean?
And then we can think about how

00:30:56.257 --> 00:31:00.000
temperature would affect those
values.

00:31:00.000 --> 00:31:04.382
Here we have a reaction with
the fast reversible step

00:31:04.382 --> 00:31:07.500
followed by another step that is
slow.

00:31:07.500 --> 00:31:11.292
We can say that the rate of
product formation,

00:31:11.292 --> 00:31:16.179
our product here is NO two,
is going to be equal to

00:31:16.179 --> 00:31:19.719
two, because two were formed,
k two,

00:31:19.719 --> 00:31:23.679
this rate constant,
times this intermediate here

00:31:23.679 --> 00:31:26.460
times the concentration of
oxygen.

00:31:26.460 --> 00:31:31.641
That is just this last step.
This slow step rate of

00:31:31.641 --> 00:31:35.298
formation of product.
But this is an intermediate,

00:31:35.298 --> 00:31:38.656
so we are not done.
We have to get rid of this

00:31:38.656 --> 00:31:41.791
intermediate.
And here, we can do it fairly

00:31:41.791 --> 00:31:46.417
efficiently, because we have a
fast reversible step followed by

00:31:46.417 --> 00:31:49.402
a slow step.
We can approximate that this

00:31:49.402 --> 00:31:53.208
step is in equilibrium.
And, if we approximate that,

00:31:53.208 --> 00:31:57.164
then we can solve for this
intermediate in terms of an

00:31:57.164 --> 00:32:02.347
equilibrium expression.
Again, the first step fast and

00:32:02.347 --> 00:32:04.850
reversible, the second step
slow.

00:32:04.850 --> 00:32:07.511
This is pretty much in
equilibrium.

00:32:07.511 --> 00:32:11.657
Not much of this intermediate
is being siphoned off to

00:32:11.657 --> 00:32:14.630
products.
We can solve by setting up an

00:32:14.630 --> 00:32:18.229
equilibrium expression.
Here is the equilibrium

00:32:18.229 --> 00:32:21.515
expression.
Equilibrium constant for Step 1

00:32:21.515 --> 00:32:25.740
equals rate constant for the
forward reaction over rate

00:32:25.740 --> 00:32:29.887
constant for the reverse
reaction equals products over

00:32:29.887 --> 00:32:33.988
reactants.
There are two reactants,

00:32:33.988 --> 00:32:38.295
two NO, so it is NO squared.
And we can solve for the

00:32:38.295 --> 00:32:41.029
concentration of the
intermediate,

00:32:41.029 --> 00:32:45.171
then, which would be k one
times NO squared.

00:32:45.171 --> 00:32:49.479
Now we can substitute that in
the overall expression,

00:32:49.479 --> 00:32:52.130
and we have this expression
here.

00:32:52.130 --> 00:32:57.183
Now our k(obs) is going to be
equal to this two k two

00:32:57.183 --> 00:33:02.142
and big K one.
This is what we need to

00:33:02.142 --> 00:33:06.335
consider, how that is affected
by temperature.

00:33:06.335 --> 00:33:10.993
Little k two is an
elementary rate constant.

00:33:10.993 --> 00:33:16.024
For an elementary reaction,
increasing temperature will

00:33:16.024 --> 00:33:20.403
always increase rate.
We know how this affected.

00:33:20.403 --> 00:33:25.155
And here is our expression that
we looked at before.

00:33:25.155 --> 00:33:30.000
Now, what about the equilibrium
constant?

00:33:30.000 --> 00:33:35.321
How do you know what is going
to happen with an equilibrium

00:33:35.321 --> 00:33:40.733
constant, if it will get bigger
or smaller with temperature?

00:33:40.733 --> 00:33:45.688
What is the equation that
relates equilibrium constants

00:33:45.688 --> 00:33:48.623
and temperature?
Van Hoff, right.

00:33:48.623 --> 00:33:52.935
It depends on delta H.
It depends on whether the

00:33:52.935 --> 00:33:56.330
reaction is endothermic or
exothermic.

00:33:56.330 --> 00:34:01.885
And here is that expression.
You can see these are really

00:34:01.885 --> 00:34:05.453
very similar expressions.
Here we have the equilibrium

00:34:05.453 --> 00:34:08.214
constants.
Delta H is our predictive tool.

00:34:08.214 --> 00:34:12.254
Whether that is endothermic or
exothermic will depend on what

00:34:12.254 --> 00:34:15.553
direction it goes.
It will depend on whether K one

00:34:15.553 --> 00:34:19.862
is bigger than k two or k two is
bigger than k one with change in

00:34:19.862 --> 00:34:22.354
temperature.
And over here we have the

00:34:22.354 --> 00:34:27.000
expression that relates rate
constants with temperature.

00:34:27.000 --> 00:34:30.206
And, in terms of sign,
that is not an issue here,

00:34:30.206 --> 00:34:33.145
because activation energy is
always positive.

00:34:33.145 --> 00:34:35.617
There is always a barrier to
overcome.

00:34:35.617 --> 00:34:38.890
That is always positive.
Never a negative barrier.

00:34:38.890 --> 00:34:42.497
There is no sign change here,
but there is an effective

00:34:42.497 --> 00:34:45.504
magnitude of that value as there
is with this.

00:34:45.504 --> 00:34:48.576
So it is not so simple.
If you have a multistep

00:34:48.576 --> 00:34:52.585
reaction, it is not always so
simple to predict the affect of

00:34:52.585 --> 00:34:56.526
temperature, because it may be
changing one thing in one way

00:34:56.526 --> 00:35:00.000
and something else in another
way.

00:35:00.000 --> 00:35:02.981
Let's consider this particular
one here.

00:35:02.981 --> 00:35:07.568
Again, little k is always going
