00:35:37.000 --> 00:35:43.749
The magnitude of the increase
or decrease will depend on the

00:35:43.749 --> 00:35:50.612
magnitude of the energy barrier
and the magnitude of delta H.

00:35:50.612 --> 00:35:57.247
If we look at this particular
example and you are told that

00:35:57.247 --> 00:36:04.110
the activation energy is a small
number, it is not a very big

00:36:04.110 --> 00:36:10.322
activation energy barrier.
And you are also told then that

00:36:10.322 --> 00:36:13.919
delta H is a big number,
and it is a big negative

00:36:13.919 --> 00:36:16.466
number, what would that mean,
then?

00:36:16.466 --> 00:36:20.662
Well, if you look at this,
if you have a small number for

00:36:20.662 --> 00:36:24.334
activation energy,
then there is not going to be a

00:36:24.334 --> 00:36:28.904
big difference between the Ks.
The rate constant is only going

00:36:28.904 --> 00:36:34.000
to increase a little bit,
because this is a small number.

00:36:34.000 --> 00:36:37.062
On the other hand,
if delta H is a big number,

00:36:37.062 --> 00:36:41.214
and you are told delta H is a
big number, then the equilibrium

00:36:41.214 --> 00:36:44.345
constant should be very
sensitive to changes in

00:36:44.345 --> 00:36:47.272
temperature.
You should see a big difference

00:36:47.272 --> 00:36:51.151
in the equilibrium constants,
because this is a really big

00:36:51.151 --> 00:36:53.670
number.
This particular reaction is an

00:36:53.670 --> 00:36:57.209
example where increasing the
temperature can actually

00:36:57.209 --> 00:37:02.578
decrease the observed rate.
And the effect is because of

00:37:02.578 --> 00:37:05.986
the delta H.
Again, a large activation

00:37:05.986 --> 00:37:11.052
energy means that the rate
constant is very sensitive to

00:37:11.052 --> 00:37:15.934
changes in temperature,
a large delta H means that the

00:37:15.934 --> 00:37:20.631
equilibrium constant is very
sensitive to changes in

00:37:20.631 --> 00:37:24.407
temperature.
Our predictors are activation

00:37:24.407 --> 00:37:29.197
energy and also delta H,
in thinking about what might

00:37:29.197 --> 00:37:35.000
happen when the temperature of a
reaction changes.

00:37:35.000 --> 00:37:39.320
And we mentioned that this is
always going to increase,

00:37:39.320 --> 00:37:43.400
rate constant will always
increase with temperature.

00:37:43.400 --> 00:37:47.800
And you can easily remember
this, that there is always a

00:37:47.800 --> 00:37:50.599
barrier.
You don't get a great deal.

00:37:50.599 --> 00:37:53.559
There is always a barrier to
overcome.

00:37:53.559 --> 00:37:57.880
And delta H can be positive or
negative, so equilibrium

00:37:57.880 --> 00:38:03.000
constants can increase or
decrease with temperature.

00:38:03.000 --> 00:38:06.840
For delta H,
magnitude of delta H indicates

00:38:06.840 --> 00:38:12.053
the magnitude of the change.
Sign of delta H indicates the

00:38:12.053 --> 00:38:16.442
direction of the change.
And, if you forget that,

00:38:16.442 --> 00:38:21.563
you can just look at the
equations and they will tell you

00:38:21.563 --> 00:38:25.312
the same thing.
Now we can come back to Le

00:38:25.312 --> 00:38:28.056
Châtelier.
We can explain those

00:38:28.056 --> 00:38:34.000
observations about how
equilibrium constants changed.

00:38:34.000 --> 00:38:38.742
And how the reaction was
affected, why you would shift in

00:38:38.742 --> 00:38:43.824
one direction versus another
when you change the temperature.

00:38:43.824 --> 00:38:48.990
Again, Le Châtelier says that a
system that is at equilibrium,

00:38:48.990 --> 00:38:53.394
if you have the system at
equilibrium and you apply a

00:38:53.394 --> 00:38:58.560
stress, the system will respond
in such a way to minimize that

00:38:58.560 --> 00:39:01.425
stress.
If you increased the

00:39:01.425 --> 00:39:05.631
temperature, the equilibrium
should shift in the endothermic

00:39:05.631 --> 00:39:07.911
direction.
That would be what the

00:39:07.911 --> 00:39:12.117
prediction would be from Le
Châtelier, because if you put in

00:39:12.117 --> 00:39:16.607
more heat the reaction wants to
respond in a way to decrease the

00:39:16.607 --> 00:39:19.174
heat.
And so it goes in the direction

00:39:19.174 --> 00:39:22.310
that absorbs heat,
the endothermic direction.

00:39:22.310 --> 00:39:26.301
This is what we talked about
before, but now we can think

00:39:26.301 --> 00:39:30.721
about this in a little bit of a
different way in terms of these

00:39:30.721 --> 00:39:36.293
reaction coordinate diagrams.
Let's look at an endothermic

00:39:36.293 --> 00:39:40.717
versus exothermic reaction.
Here we have an endothermic

00:39:40.717 --> 00:39:43.338
reaction.
We have reactants here,

00:39:43.338 --> 00:39:48.090
we have a large activation
energy in the forward direction,

00:39:48.090 --> 00:39:52.677
we have products up here,
and a smaller activation energy

00:39:52.677 --> 00:39:57.101
in the reverse direction.
For this exothermic reaction,

00:39:57.101 --> 00:40:03.000
we have a smaller activation
energy in the forward direction.

00:40:03.000 --> 00:40:06.788
And a much larger one in the
reverse direction.

00:40:06.788 --> 00:40:11.729
Our equation here would then
indicate you have an endothermic

00:40:11.729 --> 00:40:16.011
reaction, your delta E is
positive, if you have a big

00:40:16.011 --> 00:40:20.870
number for the forward minus a
small number for the reverse.

00:40:20.870 --> 00:40:25.070
That is going to give you a
positive overall number.

00:40:25.070 --> 00:40:29.435
Whereas, in this case,
if you have a small number here

00:40:29.435 --> 00:40:34.047
minus a much bigger number,
you get a negative number for

00:40:34.047 --> 00:40:38.000
delta E or an exothermic
reaction.

00:40:38.000 --> 00:40:42.050
If you are given information
about the activation energy in

00:40:42.050 --> 00:40:46.379
the forward direction and in the
reverse direction and ask if a

00:40:46.379 --> 00:40:50.360
reaction is endothermic or
exothermic, you can figure that

00:40:50.360 --> 00:40:53.502
out using this equation.
Now let's think about

00:40:53.502 --> 00:40:56.296
temperature.
If there is a small barrier,

00:40:56.296 --> 00:40:59.578
only a small barrier,
most of your molecules can

00:40:59.578 --> 00:41:03.000
probably get over that small
barrier.

00:41:03.000 --> 00:41:06.274
It's not that hard.
But if there is a very large

00:41:06.274 --> 00:41:10.244
barrier, that is a problem.
Temperature helps with the big

00:41:10.244 --> 00:41:12.125
barriers.
The small barrier,

00:41:12.125 --> 00:41:14.564
the molecules are going over
anyway.

00:41:14.564 --> 00:41:17.420
The bigger barriers,
they need extra help.

00:41:17.420 --> 00:41:20.415
They need the help of increased
temperature.

00:41:20.415 --> 00:41:24.316
If we consider what happens,
increasing temperature here,

00:41:24.316 --> 00:41:27.103
the big barrier is the forward
direction.

00:41:27.103 --> 00:41:31.422
Increasing the temperature will
make it easier to overcome this

00:41:31.422 --> 00:41:36.050
very large barrier.
It makes very little difference

00:41:36.050 --> 00:41:38.432
here.
The molecules are already doing

00:41:38.432 --> 00:41:41.409
fine getting over the small
barrier, but here,

00:41:41.409 --> 00:41:43.725
there is a big help.
What this does,

00:41:43.725 --> 00:41:47.033
then, is it shifts the
equilibrium toward products.

00:41:47.033 --> 00:41:50.737
Increasing temperature for an
endothermic reaction shifts

00:41:50.737 --> 00:41:53.847
toward products.
That is what we learned before,

00:41:53.847 --> 00:41:57.089
but we had a different
rationale for it last time.

00:41:57.089 --> 00:42:01.912
Now let's consider this case.
If you increase temperature,

00:42:01.912 --> 00:42:05.053
it is going to affect the
reverse barrier more.

00:42:05.053 --> 00:42:08.536
That is the big barrier.
This is where molecules are

00:42:08.536 --> 00:42:11.951
having a difficult time.
They are getting over that

00:42:11.951 --> 00:42:14.136
barrier already,
so in this case,

00:42:14.136 --> 00:42:18.234
when you have this exothermic
reaction, adding temperature is

00:42:18.234 --> 00:42:21.990
going to shift toward reactants.
It will shift it in the

00:42:21.990 --> 00:42:24.653
endothermic direction using up
the heat.

00:42:24.653 --> 00:42:28.000
Again, this is what we saw
before.

00:42:28.000 --> 00:42:31.658
But now we have a different
explanation for why.

00:42:31.658 --> 00:42:35.860
Again, a large activation
energy barrier means that the

00:42:35.860 --> 00:42:39.596
rate constants are very
sensitive to temperature.

00:42:39.596 --> 00:42:42.320
It is highly affected.
If it is big,

00:42:42.320 --> 00:42:45.433
it is large.
It needs temperature for the

00:42:45.433 --> 00:42:49.481
molecules to get over.
Increasing the temperature has

00:42:49.481 --> 00:42:52.360
a big effect.
Now molecules can do it.

00:42:52.360 --> 00:42:55.863
They can get over.
This is why a large barrier

00:42:55.863 --> 00:43:01.000
means that a reaction is
sensitive to temperature.

00:43:01.000 --> 00:43:03.851
Big activation energy,
big difference.

00:43:03.851 --> 00:43:07.184
Small activation energy,
not such a big difference.

